{"id":"astro-ph/0604013","submitter":"Ioav Waga","authors":"L. Amendola, M. Makler, R.R.R. Reis and I. Waga","title":"Is it possible to observationally distinguish adiabatic Quartessence\n  from LambdaCDM?","comments":"5 pages, 7 figures, revised version to appear in PRD","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. D74 (2006) 063524","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.74.063524","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The equation of state (EOS) in quartessence models interpolates between two\nstages: $p\\simeq 0$ at high energy densities and $p\\approx -\\rho$ at small\nones. In the quartessence models analyzed up to now, the EOS is convex,\nimplying increasing adiabatic sound speed ($c_{s}^{2}$) as the energy density\ndecreases in an expanding Universe. A non-negligible $c_{s}^{2}$ at recent\ntimes is the source of the matter power spectrum problem that plagued all\nconvex (non-silent) quartessence models. Viability for these cosmologies is\nonly possible in the limit of almost perfect mimicry to $\\Lambda$CDM. In this\nwork we investigate if similarity to $\\Lambda$CDM is also required in the class\nof quartessence models whose EOS changes concavity as the Universe evolves. We\nfocus our analysis in the simple case in which the EOS has a step-like shape,\nsuch that at very early times $p\\simeq0$, and at late times $p\\simeq const<0$.\nFor this class of models a non-negligible $c_{s}^{2}$ is a transient\nphenomenon, and could be relevant only at a more early epoch. We show that\nagreement with a large set of cosmological data requires that the transition\nbetween these two asymptotic states would have occurred at high redshift\n($z_t\\gtrsim38$). This leads us to conjecture that the cosmic expansion history\nof any successful non-silent quartessence is (practically) identical to the\n$\\Lambda$CDM one.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 2 Apr 2006 18:16:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 13 Sep 2006 15:11:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
