{"id":"cond-mat/0604022","submitter":"Limei Xu","authors":"Limei Xu, Isaac Ehrenberg, Sergey V. Buldyrev, H. Eugene Stanley","title":"Relation between the Liquid-Liquid Phase Transition and Dynamic Behavior\n  in the Jagla Model","comments":"5 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"J. Phys.: Condens. Matter 18, S2239 (2006)","doi":"10.1088/0953-8984/18/36/S01","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft cond-mat.stat-mech","license":null,"abstract":"  Using molecular dynamics simulations, we study a spherically-symmetric\n``two-scale'' Jagla potential with both repulsive and attractive ramps. This\npotential displays a liquid-liquid phase transition with a positively sloped\ncoexistence line ending at critical point well above the equilibrium melting\nline. We study the dynamic behavior in the vicinity of this liquid-liquid\ncritical point. We find that the dynamics in the more ordered high density\nphase (HDL) are much slower then the dynamics in the less ordered low density\nphase (LDL). Moreover, the behavior of the diffusion constant and relaxation\ntime in the HDL phase follows approximately an Arrhenius law, while in the LDL\nphase the slope of the Arrhenius fit increases upon cooling. On the other hand,\nif we cool the system at constant pressure above the critical pressure behavior\nof the dynamics smoothly changes with temperature. It resembles the behavior of\nthe LDL at high temperatures and resembles the behavior of the HDL at low\ntemperatures. This dynamic crossover happens in the vicinity of the Widom line\n(the extension of the coexistence line into the one-phase region) which also\nhas a positive slope. Our work suggests a possible general relation between a\nliquid-liquid phase transition and the change in dynamics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 2 Apr 2006 16:53:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Apr 2006 23:06:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
